  </exercise>

  <pagebreak />

  <exercise workspace="0.20%">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Where is the maximum value of each function attained?
        How do you know?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Set <m>y=0</m> and compute the <m>x</m> derivative of functions <m>f_1</m> and <m>f_4</m> at <m>x =2</m>.
        Which is steeper at <m>(2,0)</m>?
        <em>FIX!!!! One is undefined.</em>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="10%">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Repeat question 3, but use <m>y=1</m> and compute <m>x</m> derivatives at <m>x = 1</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="20%">
    <statement>
      <p>
        In CoCalc, use Sage to plot contour maps of the following functions.
        Explore the options for which contours you can include and coloring.
        Make notes about these commands in the space below.

        <ol type="a">
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(x,y) = x-y</m> <c>contour_plot(x-y, (x, -2, 2), (y, -2, 2))</c>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(x,y) = (x+y)^2</m> <c>help(contour_plot)</c>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(x,y) = xe^{-y}</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(x,y) = \sin{(x-y)}</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(x,y) = y-x^2</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(x,y) = y/x^2</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
